Mage Store
Left over from the Age of the Magi, when mages were plentiful, these robes are sturdy, but fairly common. They last a long time, rarely wearing out.
This is a magic robe.
Left over from the Age of the Magi, when mages were plentiful, these robes are sturdy, but fairly common. They last a long time, rarely wearing out.
This is a magic robe.

Woven round the brim of this helm is a light cord with a small gem set so that it rests upon the forehead of the wearer.  The magic of the headband has the power to dramatically sharpen the wearer's intellect.

Blessed by priests of Calahi the god of merchants and travel, these boots seem to make even the most arduous journey easier and more pleasant. This is accomplished not by increasing the wearer's speed, but by making him hardier and more resistant to pain. Numerous versions of these boots exist, their power varying largely in accordance with the priest who blessed them.

This is accomplished not by increasing the wearer's speed, but by making him hardier and more resistant to pain. Numerous versions of these boots exist, their power varying largely in accordance with the priest who blessed them.
Relics from the Age of the Magi, these bracers can still be found in the common gear of most adventurers. Anything that makes an adventurer quicker and harder to hit is a must-have item.

Near the end of the Age of the Magi, legends tell that the first Emporer of Valratha used hunters who seemed to resist many of the spells used by their victims. By the end of his rule, the Emporer had destroyed the majority of mages across Valratha. Even today, mages of any power are few and far between.
The crutch of shoddy thieves and cowardly paladins, these potions are well known across the face of Valratha.
These potions are in equal demand by adventurers and scholars, and see much use in the dungeons of Valratha.
Because they must constantly have their charges replenished, rods and wands in Valratha have become scarce. There simply aren't enough powerful mages to recharge these items.

Tormented by voices that incessantly attacked his mind, young Resino of Lavin begged his local church to kill him. Understanding his pain but unable to identify any specific demonic influence, the church tried crafting rings that they hoped would clear his thoughts. Unfortunately, while the rings enhanced his senses they did nothing for the voices, and Resino eventually took his own life.

Understanding his pain but unable to identify any specific demonic influence, the church tried crafting rings that they hoped would clear his thoughts. Unfortunately, while the rings enhanced his senses they did nothing for the voices, and Resino eventually took his own life.
It is rumored that these rings were created in lands across the sea from Valratha. Since no ships have ever survived such a crossing of the seas, few believe these stories.
Only a few of these rings exist, and almost all of them are owned by very powerful mages. It is a status symbol to own such a ring.
